Pre-processing¶

Involves several steps, most of which have been combined in the code sample below:

  • Selection - picked the review field only for cleaning and analysis
  • Cleaning - removed all special characters, includes expunging html tags
  • Transformation - Text is split in separate word arrays
  • Integration - performed when performing visualizations

Interpretations¶

Positive and Negative WordClouds

When observing from the positive wordcloud, positive reviews tend to skew strongly to the positive; tend to be strongly positive i.e. most positive reviews are very positive. Most positive reviews highlighted movie characters, the movie story, a scene

It is interesting when observing from the negative wordcloud. This is because negative reviews are not strongly skewed towards the negative; negative reviews are not strongly negative. This could be due to review curation, which would cull out strongly negative reviews. The size of the words 'bad' and 'good' are similar as per observation. Most negative reviews highlighted movie characters, one item/thing that might have put them off, plot and story. Minor highlights for these reviews were on the director, actor

Full Dataset

The wordcloud for all reviews had reviewers talking about scenes, characters, story, scenes, people, time. Generally Most reviews skew positively, since from the wordcloud the word 'good' seemed to have more occurences than 'bad'. This observation is as expected from a movie review text corpus

In [17]:
bigram_df = pd.DataFrame(bigram_counts.most_common(100),
                             columns=['bigram', 'count'])

bigram_df

# Create dictionary of bigrams and their counts
d = bigram_df.set_index('bigram').T.to_dict('records')

# Create network plot 
G = nx.Graph()

# Create connections between nodes
for k, v in d[0].items():
    G.add_edge(k[0], k[1], weight=(v * 10))
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(35, 35))

pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=2)

# Plot networks
nx.draw_networkx(G, pos,
                 font_size=16,
                 width=3,
                 edge_color='grey',
                 node_color='purple',
                 with_labels = False,
                 ax=ax)

# Create offset labels
for key, value in pos.items():
    x, y = value[0]+.135, value[1]+.045
    ax.text(x, y,
            s=key,
            bbox=dict(facecolor='red', alpha=0.25),
            horizontalalignment='center', fontsize=13)
    
plt.show()

Intepretations¶

The network graph shows the bigram relations, where a word is represented by a node, and the relationship is represented via an edge (connecting line). More correlated words create a tight cluster between nodes. This means that after observing one of these words in the cluster, there's is a high likelyhood the closely correlated word(s) will also be observed

As per the provided corpus, the top 20 bigram tuples produced some interesting observations. One interesting observation is (new, york) tuple, meaning most reviews touched on location (either setting of the movie, or reviewers location), of New York which happens to be one of the biggest and famous cities in USA, and the world. Another observation of interest is ('high', 'school'), meaning most reviewers watched, or most reviews were on, high-school themed movies

('special', 'effects') was number two in the bigram most common tuples, meaning most reviewers are keen on the visuals of created graphics in movies.

Discuss potential applications of the extracted patterns¶

This extracted patterns can be used for decision making on:

  • Getting more reviews on movies based on other locations, or from other locations, to get a more nuanced view on the movies industry
  • Pay special attention on special effects, ensuring these are implemented properly
  • Pay special attention to the plot/story and movie characters and actors
